1 Background

Pedal edema is a disease, where there is accumulation of fluid in the feet and lower legs. It is not threatening by itself, but can develop into other diseases like venous thrombosis which are not curable, only treatable. Edema occurs when there is excess of water and salt retention in the body by kidneys, and it may be due to weaker pumping of the blood by heart, liver cirrhosis, kidney failure, among other factors.

I aim to look at all the blood related components provided in the dataset, primarily because salts are something which are going to be high anyway, and edema later on develops into venous insufficiency or venous thrombosis, which are highly dangerous. Since these disorders too are blood related, what I want to know, is that is there any specific component of blood, which is indicative of the onset of Pedal edema? Anything, which can help us warn the people beforehand, or at least take preventive measures would be useful.

2 Research Questions

Is/are there any specific blood components, variations in which could tell us about the onset of Pedal edema?

3 My Data

This data, titled Early stage of Chronic kidney disease in Indians was collected by Dr P Soundarapandian, a senior nephrologist, working for Apollo Hospitals in the Tamil Nadu state of India, in July 2015. A total of 400 patients were screened for about 2 months, and a multitude of factors were recorded for these patients. It has 25 different variables, covering a wide range of aspects from Sodium content to bacteria concentration. Thus, it provides a myriad of variables, especially related to the components of the blood.

This data was not properly recorded, with ? replacing missing values and blanks where the data was not aligned properly. I had to align the data and re-arrange it properly. There were a lot of missing values in the data set as well, with the range of missing values going from 1 to 150.

3.1 Data Load

ckd <-  read.csv("C:\\Users\\mani\\Desktop\\Case Acad\\Spring 2018\\Ckd.csv", header=T, na.strings=c("?","NA"))

There are 400 rows and 25 columns in this data set.

3.2 Tidying, Data Cleaning and Data Management

ckd1 <- ckd %>% select(pe, ane, bp, bgr, bu, sc, hemo, wbcc, rbcc) 

ckd2 <- ckd1
ckd2 <- ckd2 %>%  mutate(pe = ifelse(pe == "yes", 1, 0))
ckd2 <- ckd2 %>%  mutate(ane = ifelse(ane == "yes", 1, 0))

I have chosen all the blood associated factors from the original dataset, and have converted two Yes/No variables, namely, pe and ane into 1/0 variables.

5 Analyses

5.1 Visualization

variables1 <- c("pe", "bgr", "hemo", "bu", "ane")

ckd2 %>%
  select(variables1) %>%   ggparcoord(alpha = .5, scale = "center", columns = 1:5, groupColumn = "pe", title = "Parallel Coord. Plot of Pedal edema, with respect to Blood glucose, Hemoglobin, Urea and Anemia")

variables2 <- c("bp", "wbcc", "rbcc", "sc", "pe")

ckd2 %>%
select(variables2) %>%   ggparcoord(alpha = .5, scale = "center", columns = 1:5, groupColumn = "pe", title = "Parallel Coord. Plot of Pedal edema, with respect to Blood pressure, WBCC, RBCC and Serum creatinine")

The parallel coordination plot is a very interesting way to visualize even 4-5 variables in a single plot. This graph, particularly, gives a description of how the different values are varying when it comes to Pedal edema. Patients with pedal edema generally have a lower rbc count and hemoglobin level, while for all the other factors, it was pretty mixed. There might be some relation between the RBC and hemoglobin vs the pedal edema.

plot(spearman2(pe ~ hemo + ane + bgr + bu + bp + wbcc + rbcc + sc, data = ckd2))

According to the spearman rho squared plot, rbc count has the highest predictive power, followed by hemoglobin levels, which is a close second, which is to be expected. The others are serum creatinine, blood urea, and anemia. I thus, decided to use the first 5 variables from the plot to make my non linear model.

mod1 <- lm(pe~rcs(rbcc, 3), data = ckd2)
mod2 <- lm(pe~rcs(rbcc, 4), data = ckd2)
mod1.aug <- augment(mod1, ckd2)
mod2.aug <- augment(mod2, ckd2)

p1 <- ggplot(ckd2, aes(x = rbcc, y = pe)) +
     geom_point() +
     geom_smooth(method = "lm", col = "black", se = F) +
     labs(title = "Linear Fit of RBC count vs Pedal Edema ") +
     theme_bw()
     
p2 <- ggplot(ckd2, aes(x = rbcc, y = pe)) +
     geom_point() +
     geom_smooth(method = "loess", col = "purple", se = F) +
     labs(title = "Loess Smooth") +
     theme_bw()
     
p3 <- ggplot(mod1.aug, aes(x = rbcc, y = pe)) +
          geom_point() +
         geom_line(aes(x = rbcc, y = .fitted), 
               col = "blue", size = 1.25) +
        labs(title = "RCS, 3 knots") +
        theme_bw()
        
p4 <- ggplot(mod2.aug, aes(x = rbcc, y = pe)) +
            geom_point() +
           geom_line(aes(x = rbcc, y = .fitted), 
            col = "blue", size = 1.25) +
          labs(title = "RCS, 4 knots") +
         theme_bw()
         
gridExtra::grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, p4, nrow = 2)

This plot is about the splines, and how good do different polynomial or linear lines fit the distribution of rbc count and pedal edema. A lot of values were removed from the graph, because they were missing.
I chose to go forward with the spline with 4 knots, especially since there isnt a major difference in the graphs with 3 and 4 knots.

5.2.4 Nomogram

plot(nomogram(m_imp_model1, fun = plogis))

The Brier value is 0.117, indicating that the model is calibrated pretty well, with the calibration plot showing Mean absolute error=0.017, and Mean squared error=0.00063. As the predicted probability of pedal edema goes higher, initially, the calibration s such that the actual probability of one having pedal edema is slightly higher, while after a certain point, the actual probability goes below the predicted probability.

The AIC and BIC values are: 310.33 and 342.26 respectively.

Thus, according to the nomogram, and the p value, RBC count is the most important factor for prediction of pedal edema.

The calibration plot shows that the actual probability of one having pedal edema is slightly higher than the predicted probability, while after a certain point, the actual probability goes below the predicted probability.

The AIC and BIC values are: 306.07 and 341.99 respectively, so, slightly lower than model 1.

5.3.4 Nomogram

plot(nomogram(m_imp_model2, fun = plogis))

The nomogram shows how significant the RBC count is in order to determine Pedal edema.

6 Conclusions

Irrespective of the model, RBC count is the most important factor for prediction of pedal edema, and the people with lower RBC values are at higher risk for pedal edema. This is what I wanted to find out, since people with abnormally lower count of RBCs can be warned of developing pedal edema or venous thrombosis, thus enabling us to take preventive measures on time. Another conclusion to take home was that neither hemoglobin nor creatinine arent major players in assessing risk of pedal edema, though they do contribute something, so there must be another protein in the blood which is highly indicative of occurring of Edema.

Multiple imputation can be really confusing, and combining it with Non linear plots and Logistic regression increases the said confusion.
